At the end of ch.~\ref{ch:time}, we saw that because of the way time works in our
universe, it is not possible for light and matter to be made out of particles,
as envisioned by Isaac Newton. Instead, our universe must be made out of waves
(or, as we'll see when we study quantum physics at the end of this course,
things that have both particle and wave characteristics). In this chapter we
will study mechanical waves, which are made out of vibrations of physical objects.
These are concrete and easy to conceptualize. Then in ch.~\ref{ch:em-waves} we will
turn to electromagnetic waves, such as visible light, which will be our first
example of the \emph{fundamental} kinds of waves that the universe is ultimately
composed of.

